CLASSICAL SWINE FEVER - GUATEMALA: OIE
**************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: 9 May 2006
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Disease Alert, 8 May 2006 [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/Messages/060508GTM.htm>

Classical Swine Fever in Guatemala
(Date of previous outbreak of classical swine fever in Guatemala
reported to the OIE: June 2003).
Translation of information received on 5 May 2006 from Dr Miguel
Angel Azanon Robles, Animal Health Director, Standards and
Regulations Department, Ministry of Agriculture, Livestock and Food
Supply (MAGA), Guatemala:
Report date: 5 May 2006.
Reason for immediate notification: re-occurrence of a listed disease
or infection in a country or zone/compartment following a report
declaring the outbreak(s) ended.
Identification of agent: classical swine fever virus.
Date of start of the event: 20 Apr 2006.
An outbreak of classical swine fever has been reported at Lo de Coy
village, in Mixto municipality, in a herd with 49 animals (33
suckling pigs, 4 rearing pigs, 10 breeders and 2 boars). 30 pigs are
dead and 19 have been destroyed. For a map of Guatemala see
<http://www.ieq.org/images/guatemala_map.gif>.
The diagnosis has been established using PCR on 27 Apr 2006 by the
MAGA Reference Central Laboratory (Ministry of Agriculture and
Livestock), Managua, Nicaragua.
52 animals have been vaccinated with an attenuated virus strain
PAV-250 vaccine.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Most of the countries in Central America have reported outbreaks of
Classical Swine Fever over the past 10 years. Costa Rica as well as
Guatemala had outbreaks in 2003, El Salvador in 2001 and Honduras has
been reporting continuously since 1996. Belize, on the other hand,
has not had an outbreak since 1988. - Mod.PC]
